.TH STRLOG 9 "$Date: 2004/08/24 08:42:47 $" "$Name:  $" "Linux Fast-STREAMS DDI/DKI"
.\"
.\"
.SH NAME
.B strlog
\- pass a message to the \fISTREAMS\fR logger
.\"
.\"
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
.B #include <sys/stream.h>
.br
.B #include <sys/strlog.h>
.HP
.BI "int strlog(short " mid ", short " sid ", char " level ", unsigned short " flags ", char *" fmt ", " ... );
.\"
.\"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.TP
.I mid
specifies the STREAMS module id
.TP
.I sid
specifies the STREAMS minor device number associated with the module.
.TP
.I level
specifies a priority level.
.TP
.I flags
log flags specifying the severity and options associated with the STREAMS log.
.TP
.I fmt
provides the
.BR printf (3)
style format string.
.TP
.I ...
provides the arguments for the
.BR printf (3)
style format string.
.\"
.\"
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
.BR strlog ()
passes a 
.I STREAMS
log message to the
.I STREAMS
logger.
.PP
.I mid
identifies the
.I STREAMS
module id associated with the
.I STREAMS
driver or module generating the log.
.I sid
is the minor device node within the
.I STREAMS
driver or module
to which the log applies.
.I level
indicates the priority level of the log message with respect to other log
messages in the same class.
.I flags
can contain a bitwise OR of zero or more of the following flags:
.TP \w'SL_NOPUTBUF\(em'u
.B SL_FATAL
log with
.BR syslog (3)
.I level
of 
.BR LOG_CRIT .
.PD 0
.TP
.B SL_ERROR
log with
.BR syslog (3)
.I level
of 
.BR LOG_ERR .
.TP
.B SL_WARN
log with
.BR syslog (3)
.I level
of 
.BR LOG_WARNING .
.TP
.B SL_NOTE
log with
.BR syslog (3)
.I level
of 
.BR LOG_NOTICE .
.TP
.B SL_CONSOLE
log with
.BR syslog (3)
.I level
of 
.BR LOG_INFO .
.TP
.B SL_TRACE
log with
.BR syslog (3)
.I level
of 
.BR LOG_DEBUG .
.TP
.B SL_NOTIFY
indicates that a copy of the log should be mailed to the system administrator.
.TP
.B SL_NOPUTBUF
indicates that the log should not be buffered.
.PD
.\"
.\"
.SH RETURN
.PP
Upon success,
.BR strlog ()
dispatches the log to the logger and returns one (1).
Upon failure,
.BR strlog ()
returns zero (0).
.BR strlog ()
fails whenever the message is not seen by all the readers.
.\"
.\"
.SH ERRORS
.PP
When
.BR strlog ()
fails, it returns zero (0).
.BR strlog ()
fails when it cannot dispatch the log message to the logger.
.\"
.\"
.SH CONTEXT
.PP
.BR strlog ()
can be called from any context.
.\"
.\"
.SH MP-STREAMS
.PP
.BR strlog ()
is MP-safe, however it takes global spin locks and suppresses interrupts to
accomplish this.
See
.IR "\*(lqCOMPATIBILITY\*(rq" ,
below.
.\"
.\"
.SH NOTICES
.PP
.BR strlog ()
always logs with
.BR syslog (3)
.I facility
of
.BR LOG_KERN .
.PP
.BR strlog ()
prefixes the string:
.BI \*(lqstrlog( xxx )[ yyy , zzz "]: \*(rq"
onto the beginning of log messages, where:
.I xxx
is the
.I level
argument,
.I yyy
is the
.I mid
argument, and
.I zzz
is the
.I sid
argument.
.PP
As
.B Linux
does not have a
.I STREAMS
logger, the BSD
.BR syslog (8)
facilities apply.
.PP
.BR strlog ()
always returns success.
.\"
.\"
.SH "SEE ALSO"
.PP
.BR printf (3),
.BR syslogd (2),
.BR syslogd (3),
.BR syslogd (8),
.BR printk (9),
.BR cmn_err (9).
.\"
.\"
.SH BUGS
.PP
The
.B SL_NOTIFY
and
.B SL_NOPUTBUF
flags do not function as described.
See
.IR "\*(lqCOMPATIBILITY\*(rq" ,
below.
.\"
.\"
.SH COMPATIBILITY
.PP
.BR strlog ()
is source-level compatible with SVR 4.2 MP DDI/DKI,
.[
usldk
.]
.IR AIX \(rg,
.IR HP-UX \(rg,
.IR OSF/1 \(rg,
.IR Solaris \(rg,
.IR UnixWare \(rg
and
.IR UXP/V \(rg
with the portability considerations:
.IP \(em \w'\(em\(em'u
.IR AIX \(rg
does not document the
.I flags
argument.
.IP \(em
.IR AIX \(rg,
.IR HP-UX \(rg,
.IR OSF/1 \(rg,
.IR Solaris \(rg
and
.IR UXP/V \(rg
do not document the
.B SL_NOPUTBUF
flag.
.IP \(em
The
.B SL_NOPUTBUF
flag is provided for
.IR UnixWare \(rg
source compatibility.
.BR strlog ()
ignores this flag.
.IP \(em
.IR OSF/1 \(rg
does not document the
.BR SL_FATAL ", " SL_WARN ", " SL_NOTE ", " SL_NOTIFY " or " SL_NOPUTBUF
flags.
.IP \(em
The
.B SL_NOTIFY
flags is supposed to send a copy of the log to the system administrator.  As
.B Linux
does not actually have a STREAMS based logger (although it does use
.IR \*(lq/dev/log\*(rq )
the
.BR syslogd (8)
facilities under
.B Linux
should be used instead.
Therefore,
.BR strlog ()
ignores this flag.
.IP \(em
.BR strlog ()
takes a global spin lock to protect generation of the log buffer and
.BR printk (9)
does the same.
Under
.IR AIX \(rg,
.IR HP-UX \(rg,
.IR OSF/1 \(rg,
.IR Solaris \(rg,
.IR UnixWare \(rg
and
.IR UXP/V \(rg,
.BR strlog ()
does not take global locks and can be executed concurrently.  This is one
thing that normally distinguishes
.BR strlog ()
from
.BR cmn_err (9).
.PP
.I LiS
.[
LiS
.]
does not provide this function.
.IP \(em
Binary compatibility is not guaranteed.
.PP
See
.BR STREAMS (9)
for additional compatibility considerations.
.\"
.\"
